widgets_values:
## High detail mode ⮕
This makes the frames significantly sharper by using two IPAs - but also each frame consumes twice as much RAM.

## Set low and high point of influence strength ⮕
The number are the range the strength runs from and to - the first value is the starting point, the middle is the peak, while the ending is the ending point.
Find the settings confusing and hard to understand? This is part of why we made [Dough](https://github.com/banodoco/dough) :)

## Set duration of frame influence ⮕
1.0 equals around the distance between this and the next frames, 2.0 equals twice this. You can set these values for each frame individually in the field below. The first value is the influence on the frame before, the second is on the frame after.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
## The magic

This is where your motion masking comes into effect. To improve movement in selected areas I highly suggest you mask the original images with a mask in the area you would most like to highlight movement (Relative to other areas)

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
## Motion for the background mask 

The brightness can also be changed here to decrease the background overall influence on background motion
Generally this can all be ignored for the masking - it does it automatically. Though you may run into issues if you aren't using a typical subject in the midground/background image.

## Setting frame position ⮕
Setting linear frame distribution makes the frames spaced out by the linear value - for example, if it's set to 16, the frames will be at positions 0, 16, 32, etc. If you set type to dynamic, you'll need to enter the values in the text box below.

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
## Background details

It's expected that we will want some subtle background movement. This helps to pick up those details for the motion scale. You can adjust HDR settings to decrease specific areas of detail OR use the image brightness adjustment for global decrease in background movement to the right.

## Understanding the settings
There are 3 main settings:
- Key frame position - Length of influence - Strength of influence
The type_of fields decide whether each of settings are the same for each frame or different.
When the type has been set to 'linear', you can adjust the value for every in with the _value fields.
When the type is set to 'dynamic', the text box below each setting are for the individual values - follow the format provided to set values for each frame.
Get_tile_width and Get_tile_height connect from the Image_Group through set/get
Set_tile_width and Set_tile_height connect to the Upscaler Group through set/get

This may need adjustments to the foreground depth sliders to isolate the foreground. Suggest bypassing the sampler node while you get this right. 

Though it's not the end of the world if it's not perfect if the midground looks good.

widgets_values:
regional prompting for the depth layers

upscale context options - context overlap 4 -> 2

steps: 10
n_repeat: 10
regulaizer_strength: 0.020
reduction_method: median
max_iter: 5
tol: 0.001000

denoise_steps: steps per depth map, increase for accuracy in exchange of processing time

n_repeat: amount of iterations to be ensembled into single depth map, increase for accuracy in exchange of processing time

n_repeat_batch_size: how many of the n_repeats are processed as a batch, if you have the VRAM this can match the n_repeats for faster processing

invert: marigold by default produces depth map where black is front, for controlnets etc. we want the opposite

regularizer_strength, reduction_method, max_iter, tol (tolerance) are settings for the ensembling process, don't fully know how to use them yet.

It can pretty memory hungry, and slow, fp16 halves the memory use. Marigold is meant to be run around 768p resolution so resizing is recommended, at higher res your mileage may wary. I added a remap node to see the full range better, and OpenEXR node to save the full range, works wonders compared to default png when used in VFX/3D modeling software.

# SuperBeasts Smooth Motion

-This workflow builds on POMs Batch Creative Interpolation 

Description: 

We determine foreground, midground and background details as a mask to control motion scaling in Animate Diff. This works on the assumption that foreground elements are likely to have more movement while background movement is more subtle.

Motion is generally smoother as such you may need to plan your keyframes more carefully. 

Highly suggested that prompt scheduling is also used. 
## Simple motion controls: 

- Mask areas of your image where motion should be focussed (Highly suggested)
- Use Animate Diff Motion scaling settings to inc/decrease the amount of animation based on the mask.


## Upscaling
Builds off upon the Super Badass Upscaler from Cerspence and Relic

# A brief guide
## Philosophy for getting the most from this:
This isn’t a tool like text to video that will perform well out of the box - it’s more like a paint brush, an artistic tool that you need to figure out how to get the best from.
Through trial and error, you'll need to build an understanding of how the motion and settings work, what its limitations are, which inputs work best with it, etc.
If you can figure out how to wield it, this approach can provide enough control for you to make beautiful things that match your imagination precisely.
## How to use this:
1.Select a folder with the images in them above. The most important thing that will influence the quality of your creation is the input images.
2.Try the basic settings to start. Based on the resulting generation, try to understand what happened - you can learn about the settings and observe the graphs to the right.
3.Tweak the settings until you achieve your desired effect.
## What this will & won't be suitable for: I believe that this will be good for a wide range of storytelling-driven and abstract motion. However, it probably won't be good for complex motion - other approaches like vid2vid are far more suitable for this. ## If you're having problems:
First, download the latest version of this workflow from [here](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/peteromallet/steerable-motion/main/demo/creative_interpolation_example.json) and get the latest version of the node from Comfy Manager.
If that doesn't work, drop into [our Discord](https://discord.gg/V72vk8T67n) and share your problem and I'll try to help ASAP.
## Want to join a community of people who are pushing open source models to their technical and artistic limits?
You're welcome to join [our Discord](https://discord.gg/UJf6aum7WZ).
Please share anything you generate in the steerable-motion channel.

## To download these models from Comfy Manager
On the bar on the right, click "Manager", then click "Install Models" and search up the below - the models that show for those queries should be the right ones:

- For Animatediff, search: v3\_sd15\_mm - For SparseCtrl, search: v3\_sd15\_sparsectrl - For s3\_15 adapter, search: v3\_sd15\_adapter - For Clip Vision, search: CLIP-ViT-H-14 - For ControlNet Tile, search: tile - For IP-Adapter-Plus, search: plus\_sd15.safetensors

For the VAE and styling model, *make sure to use SD 1.5 models*.
